                        "uuid": "d9d7d35d-3614-4146-bd1e-f229501f51ce",
                        "title": "Shuttle launches XPC X200 mini PC",
                        "slug": "shuttle-launches-xpc-x200-mini-pc",
                        "mobiledoc": "{\"version\":\"0.3.1\",\"markups\":[],\"atoms\":[],\"cards\":[[\"markdown\",{\"cardName\":\"card-markdown\",\"markdown\":\"As you might already know I am not a big fan of the Intel Core 2 Duo, but I just could not resist this PC simply because of the form factor, just look at it, it simply has a size of an A4 sized book, hey even my Windows 2003 reference book is bigger, \\n![XPC X200](/content/images/2013/Dec/x200.jpg)\\nand guess what it can also stand like a Wii, Powered by your choice of dual-core / Celeron M Intel processors, this wee machine also touts Intel's GMA950 integrated graphics set, a hybrid TV tuner for analog / DVB-T reception, SATA hard drive, up to 2GB of DDR2 RAM, 7.1-channel HD audio, FM radio tuner, dual-layer DVD burner, built-in 802.11b/g, PS/2 connectors, DVI output, multi-format flash card reader, an audio input jack, and an IR remote to boot. Notably, it managed to lose the FireWire and S-Video ports found on the X100, but it does boast five USB 2.0 ports in a feeble attempt to compensate. There are available in two versions and while the somewhat stripped X200BA will run you just $972 (Rs.45,000), the beefed-up X200MA will demand at least $1,240(Rs.62,000) depending on options.\"}]],\"sections\":[[10,0]],\"ghostVersion\":\"3.0\"}",
                        "html": "<!--kg-card-begin: markdown--><p>As you might already know I am not a big fan of the Intel Core 2 Duo, but I just could not resist this PC simply because of the form factor, just look at it, it simply has a size of an A4 sized book, hey even my Windows 2003 reference book is bigger,<br>\n<img src=\"/content/images/2013/Dec/x200.jpg\" alt=\"XPC X200\" loading=\"lazy\"><br>\nand guess what it can also stand like a Wii, Powered by your choice of dual-core / Celeron M Intel processors, this wee machine also touts Intel's GMA950 integrated graphics set, a hybrid TV tuner for analog / DVB-T reception, SATA hard drive, up to 2GB of DDR2 RAM, 7.1-channel HD audio, FM radio tuner, dual-layer DVD burner, built-in 802.11b/g, PS/2 connectors, DVI output, multi-format flash card reader, an audio input jack, and an IR remote to boot. Notably, it managed to lose the FireWire and S-Video ports found on the X100, but it does boast five USB 2.0 ports in a feeble attempt to compensate. There are available in two versions and while the somewhat stripped X200BA will run you just $972 (Rs.45,000), the beefed-up X200MA will demand at least $1,240(Rs.62,000) depending on options.</p>\n<!--kg-card-end: markdown-->",
                        "comment_id": "17",
                        "plaintext": "As you might already know I am not a big fan of the Intel Core 2 Duo, but I just\ncould not resist this PC simply because of the form factor, just look at it, it\nsimply has a size of an A4 sized book, hey even my Windows 2003 reference book\nis bigger,\n\nand guess what it can also stand like a Wii, Powered by your choice of dual-core\n/ Celeron M Intel processors, this wee machine also touts Intel's GMA950\nintegrated graphics set, a hybrid TV tuner for analog / DVB-T reception, SATA\nhard drive, up to 2GB of DDR2 RAM, 7.1-channel HD audio, FM radio tuner,\ndual-layer DVD burner, built-in 802.11b/g, PS/2 connectors, DVI output,\nmulti-format flash card reader, an audio input jack, and an IR remote to boot.\nNotably, it managed to lose the FireWire and S-Video ports found on the X100,\nbut it does boast five USB 2.0 ports in a feeble attempt to compensate. There\nare available in two versions and while the somewhat stripped X200BA will run\nyou just $972 (Rs.45,000), the beefed-up X200MA will demand at least\n$1,240(Rs.62,000) depending on options.",
