                        "id": "5a96fda57fc8fb601adea2bf",
                        "uuid": "7217d599-34b8-4277-a2d6-964b36c0edba",
                        "title": "Reset your SQL Server login",
                        "slug": "reset-your-sql-server-login",
                        "mobiledoc": "{\"version\":\"0.3.1\",\"markups\":[],\"atoms\":[],\"cards\":[[\"markdown\",{\"cardName\":\"card-markdown\",\"markdown\":\"Recently I faced a situation where the SQL Server was setup but no one knew the login, and the SQL server was not configured in Mixed Mode Authentication, so how do you recover from this situation other than re installing the instance,\\r\\nStop the running instance and then open up command prompt in Binn directory on the instance which would be something like\\r\\n<pre lang=\\\"bash\\\">\\r\\nc:\\\\Program Files\\\\Microsoft SQL Server\\\\MSSQL...\\\\Binn \\r\\n</pre>\\r\\nRun the following command\\r\\n<pre lang=\\\"bash\\\">\\r\\nsqlservr.exe -m\\\"SQLCMD\\\"\\r\\n</pre>\\r\\nThis would start the instance in single user mode, now open up another command prompt in the same directory\\r\\nand then run \\\"SQLCMD\\\"\\r\\nand execute the following statements based on requirement\\r\\n\\r\\nIf you want to add a windows user use\\r\\n<pre lang=\\\"sql\\\">\\r\\ncreate login [DOMAIN\\\\USERNAME] from windows;\\r\\nEXEC sys.sp_addsrvrolemember @loginame = N'DOMAIN\\\\USERNAME', @rolename = N'sysadmin';\\r\\nGO;\\r\\n</pre>\\r\\n\\r\\nTo add a SQL Server Login use (remember this works only if mixed mode authentication is enabled)\\r\\n<pre lang=\\\"sql\\\">\\r\\nCREATE LOGIN [testAdmin] WITH PASSWORD=N'test@1234', DEFAULT_DATABASE=[master];\\r\\nEXEC sys.sp_addsrvrolemember @loginame = N'testAdmin', @rolename = N'sysadmin';\\r\\nGO;\\r\\n</pre>\\r\\n\\r\\nnow exit SQLCMD and also do CTRL+C on first window to stop instance and restart the instance in regular mode.\"}]],\"sections\":[[10,0]],\"ghostVersion\":\"3.0\"}",
                        "html": "<!--kg-card-begin: markdown--><p>Recently I faced a situation where the SQL Server was setup but no one knew the login, and the SQL server was not configured in Mixed Mode Authentication, so how do you recover from this situation other than re installing the instance,<br>\nStop the running instance and then open up command prompt in Binn directory on the instance which would be something like</p>\n<pre lang=\"bash\">\nc:\\Program Files\\Microsoft SQL Server\\MSSQL...\\Binn \n</pre>\n<p>Run the following command</p>\n<pre lang=\"bash\">\nsqlservr.exe -m\"SQLCMD\"\n</pre>\n<p>This would start the instance in single user mode, now open up another command prompt in the same directory<br>\nand then run &quot;SQLCMD&quot;<br>\nand execute the following statements based on requirement</p>\n<p>If you want to add a windows user use</p>\n<pre lang=\"sql\">\ncreate login [DOMAIN\\USERNAME] from windows;\nEXEC sys.sp_addsrvrolemember @loginame = N'DOMAIN\\USERNAME', @rolename = N'sysadmin';\nGO;\n</pre>\n<p>To add a SQL Server Login use (remember this works only if mixed mode authentication is enabled)</p>\n<pre lang=\"sql\">\nCREATE LOGIN [testAdmin] WITH PASSWORD=N'test@1234', DEFAULT_DATABASE=[master];\nEXEC sys.sp_addsrvrolemember @loginame = N'testAdmin', @rolename = N'sysadmin';\nGO;\n</pre>\n<p>now exit SQLCMD and also do CTRL+C on first window to stop instance and restart the instance in regular mode.</p>\n<!--kg-card-end: markdown-->",
                        "comment_id": "109",
                        "plaintext": "Recently I faced a situation where the SQL Server was setup but no one knew the\nlogin, and the SQL server was not configured in Mixed Mode Authentication, so\nhow do you recover from this situation other than re installing the instance,\nStop the running instance and then open up command prompt in Binn directory on\nthe instance which would be something like\n\n\nc:\\Program Files\\Microsoft SQL Server\\MSSQL...\\Binn \n\n\nRun the following command\n\n\nsqlservr.exe -m\"SQLCMD\"\n\n\nThis would start the instance in single user mode, now open up another command\nprompt in the same directory\nand then run \"SQLCMD\"\nand execute the following statements based on requirement\n\nIf you want to add a windows user use\n\n\ncreate login [DOMAIN\\USERNAME] from windows;\nEXEC sys.sp_addsrvrolemember @loginame = N'DOMAIN\\USERNAME', @rolename = N'sysadmin';\nGO;\n\n\nTo add a SQL Server Login use (remember this works only if mixed mode\nauthentication is enabled)\n\n\nCREATE LOGIN [testAdmin] WITH PASSWORD=N'test@1234', DEFAULT_DATABASE=[master];\nEXEC sys.sp_addsrvrolemember @loginame = N'testAdmin', @rolename = N'sysadmin';\nGO;\n\n\nnow exit SQLCMD and also do CTRL+C on first window to stop instance and restart\nthe instance in regular mode.",
