                        "title": "Custom Information in Asp.net Identity Cookie/ Ticket",
                        "slug": "custom-information-in-asp-net-identity-cookie-ticket",
                        "mobiledoc": "{\"version\":\"0.3.1\",\"markups\":[],\"atoms\":[],\"cards\":[[\"markdown\",{\"cardName\":\"card-markdown\",\"markdown\":\"With MVC 5 Asp.net has done away with the Forms based authentication (for good) and has replaced that with the OWIN Security Middleware,\\n\\nBrock Allen has writter an nice post summarizing the basics \\n> [A primer on OWIN cookie authentication middleware](http://brockallen.com/2013/10/24/a-primer-on-owin-cookie-authentication-middleware-for-the-asp-net-developer/)\\n\\nBecause the identity is claim based you can add additional claim to the user for later use.\\n\\nIf you are just looking to add information using the existing ApplicationOAuthProvider Update the code to read.\\n\\n<script src=\\\"https://gist.github.com/anonymous/8349468.js\\\"></script>\\n\\nNote that I am adding a singe claim called E-mail, and i am also using both cookie and ticket.\\n\\nTo Access the Claims you can\\n`var context = (OwinContext)HttpContext.Current.GetOwinContext();\\nvar owinUser = context.Authentication.User; var claims = owinUser.Claims;`\"}]],\"sections\":[[10,0]],\"ghostVersion\":\"3.0\"}",
                        "html": "<!--kg-card-begin: markdown--><p>With MVC 5 Asp.net has done away with the Forms based authentication (for good) and has replaced that with the OWIN Security Middleware,</p>\n<p>Brock Allen has writter an nice post summarizing the basics</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p><a href=\"http://brockallen.com/2013/10/24/a-primer-on-owin-cookie-authentication-middleware-for-the-asp-net-developer/\">A primer on OWIN cookie authentication middleware</a></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Because the identity is claim based you can add additional claim to the user for later use.</p>\n<p>If you are just looking to add information using the existing ApplicationOAuthProvider Update the code to read.</p>\n<script src=\"https://gist.github.com/anonymous/8349468.js\"></script>\n<p>Note that I am adding a singe claim called E-mail, and i am also using both cookie and ticket.</p>\n<p>To Access the Claims you can<br>\n<code>var context = (OwinContext)HttpContext.Current.GetOwinContext(); var owinUser = context.Authentication.User; var claims = owinUser.Claims;</code></p>\n<!--kg-card-end: markdown-->",
                        "comment_id": "133",
                        "plaintext": "With MVC 5 Asp.net has done away with the Forms based authentication (for good)\nand has replaced that with the OWIN Security Middleware,\n\nBrock Allen has writter an nice post summarizing the basics\n\nA primer on OWIN cookie authentication middleware\n[http://brockallen.com/2013/10/24/a-primer-on-owin-cookie-authentication-middleware-for-the-asp-net-developer/]\n\nBecause the identity is claim based you can add additional claim to the user for\nlater use.\n\nIf you are just looking to add information using the existing\nApplicationOAuthProvider Update the code to read.\n\nNote that I am adding a singe claim called E-mail, and i am also using both\ncookie and ticket.\n\nTo Access the Claims you can\nvar context = (OwinContext)HttpContext.Current.GetOwinContext(); var owinUser =\ncontext.Authentication.User; var claims = owinUser.Claims;",
