                        "id": "5eb7e70abf74b02f4ee0d32d",
                        "uuid": "82d407ad-3dc1-45cd-9c1f-83f3af797e53",
                        "title": "Nuget Workflow on Azure DevOps",
                        "slug": "nuget-workflow-on-azure-devops",
                        "mobiledoc": "{\"version\":\"0.3.1\",\"atoms\":[],\"cards\":[[\"html\",{\"html\":\"<script src=\\\"https://gist.github.com/nareshjois/c2acaf2b5cefebb0751cb354297880f2.js\\\"></script>\"}],[\"image\",{\"src\":\"/content/images/2020/05/image.png\"}]],\"markups\":[[\"a\",[\"href\",\"https://github.com/RicoSuter/DNT\"]],[\"a\",[\"href\",\"https://github.com/RicoSuter/DNT#switch-to-projects\"]]],\"sections\":[[1,\"p\",[[0,[],0,\"Our .net project has grown quite a bit in the last few years, and we recently switched over to Azure Devops. This not just gave us access to Pipelines but also access to artifact repository where you can setup private Nuget feeds. Our project itself was strcutred to be modular so it was easy to break out components and make them as seperate packages, there were a few steps needed to completly automate the worflow, \"]]],[1,\"h2\",[[0,[],0,\"Settting up the build test pipeline\"]]],[1,\"p\",[[0,[],0,\"The following is the entire pipeline bascially following \"]]],[1,\"p\",[[0,[],0,\"Install Nuget > Nuget Restore > Run Test suite > Package Nuget > Publish to Feed\"]]],[10,0],[1,\"p\",[[0,[],0,\"while the steps themselves are self explanatory, the only additional thing we have done is make build to follow semantic versioning by using variables.\"]]],[1,\"p\",[[0,[],0,\"The nice thing about this is test results are integrated right in the UI\"]]],[10,1],[1,\"p\",[[0,[],0,\"(Next would be setup code coverage report)\"]]],[1,\"h2\",[[0,[],0,\"Debugging Local\"]]],[1,\"p\",[[0,[],0,\"There are cases in which we wanted to debug the packages as part to the main project. Here's where the nice dotnet tool \"],[0,[0],1,\"DNT\"],[0,[],0,\" comes in \"]]],[1,\"p\",[[0,[],0,\"Follwing the instructions \"],[0,[1],1,\"https://github.com/RicoSuter/DNT#switch-to-projects\"],[0,[],0,\" a simple json file and two batch files later we have a completed local debug workflow. \"]]],[1,\"p\",[]]],\"ghostVersion\":\"3.0\"}",
                        "html": "<p>Our .net project has grown quite a bit in the last few years, and we recently switched over to Azure Devops. This not just gave us access to Pipelines but also access to artifact repository where you can setup private Nuget feeds. Our project itself was strcutred to be modular so it was easy to break out components and make them as seperate packages, there were a few steps needed to completly automate the worflow, </p><h2 id=\"settting-up-the-build-test-pipeline\">Settting up the build test pipeline</h2><p>The following is the entire pipeline bascially following </p><p>Install Nuget &gt; Nuget Restore &gt; Run Test suite &gt; Package Nuget &gt; Publish to Feed</p><!--kg-card-begin: html--><script src=\"https://gist.github.com/nareshjois/c2acaf2b5cefebb0751cb354297880f2.js\"></script><!--kg-card-end: html--><p>while the steps themselves are self explanatory, the only additional thing we have done is make build to follow semantic versioning by using variables.</p><p>The nice thing about this is test results are integrated right in the UI</p><figure class=\"kg-card kg-image-card\"><img src=\"/content/images/2020/05/image.png\" class=\"kg-image\" alt loading=\"lazy\"></figure><p>(Next would be setup code coverage report)</p><h2 id=\"debugging-local\">Debugging Local</h2><p>There are cases in which we wanted to debug the packages as part to the main project. Here's where the nice dotnet tool <a href=\"https://github.com/RicoSuter/DNT\">DNT</a> comes in </p><p>Follwing the instructions <a href=\"https://github.com/RicoSuter/DNT#switch-to-projects\">https://github.com/RicoSuter/DNT#switch-to-projects</a> a simple json file and two batch files later we have a completed local debug workflow. </p>",
                        "comment_id": "5eb7e70abf74b02f4ee0d32d",
                        "plaintext": "Our .net project has grown quite a bit in the last few years, and we recently\nswitched over to Azure Devops. This not just gave us access to Pipelines but\nalso access to artifact repository where you can setup private Nuget feeds. Our\nproject itself was strcutred to be modular so it was easy to break out\ncomponents and make them as seperate packages, there were a few steps needed to\ncompletly automate the worflow, \n\nSettting up the build test pipeline\nThe following is the entire pipeline bascially following \n\nInstall Nuget > Nuget Restore > Run Test suite > Package Nuget > Publish to Feed\n\nwhile the steps themselves are self explanatory, the only additional thing we\nhave done is make build to follow semantic versioning by using variables.\n\nThe nice thing about this is test results are integrated right in the UI\n\n(Next would be setup code coverage report)\n\nDebugging Local\nThere are cases in which we wanted to debug the packages as part to the main\nproject. Here's where the nice dotnet tool DNT\n[https://github.com/RicoSuter/DNT] comes in \n\nFollwing the instructions https://github.com/RicoSuter/DNT#switch-to-projects a\nsimple json file and two batch files later we have a completed local debug\nworkflow.",
